@flexiarg relationship-coherence/low-pressure-bid
@title Attach the Exit to the Invitation
@sigils [🚪/請]
@keywords bid, invitation, no-pressure, graceful-out, consent, opt-in, non-coercive
@audience correspondents, anyone extending recurring invitations
@references [relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring relationship-coherence/narrative-suspension]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-03-20 — Joe pairs a band-event invitation with 'no pressure of course'; reinforced 2026-03-27 ('if you're otherwise occupied/engaged I won't be offended!') and made a standing style ('Totally your choice which to join-or-not', 2026-05-15; 'no worries either way'). The move recurs on both sides across the whole corpus."]
@tone practical
@style pattern

! conclusion: Build the permission-to-decline into the invitation itself, so every bid arrives with its own exit; this is what keeps bids frequent, honest, and safe to make.

  + context: A relationship advances on bids for connection — walks, dinners, calls, sleepovers, gigs. The corpus is dense with them, and almost every one ships with an explicit out. That is not hedging; it is the mechanism that keeps the bid-rate high.

  + IF:
    you want to invite the other into a plan, but a bare ask would put them on the spot to protect your feelings.

  + HOWEVER:
    an invitation with no exit converts declining into a small rejection to be managed; over time the recipient either over-commits or stops being asked. A bid that coerces poisons the next bid.

  + THEN:
    name the out in the same breath as the ask ('no pressure', 'I won't be offended', 'whatever you decide', 'no worries either way') — and mean it, receiving a decline without cost.

  + BECAUSE:
    the visible exit is what makes the yes real: consent that could have been no is worth more, and cheap declines keep the channel open for the next invitation. Frequency of bids, not success rate of any one bid, is the coherence signal.

  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: declines are met without sulk and the bid-rate stays high on both sides. Failing when: outs are stated but declines are punished (the low-pressure-bid collapses into its opposite — see the Bateson double-bind in collaboration-coherence/navel-gazing).
